EcoPuck file processing 3: Calculation of spikes

Load EcoPuck data. All data have been cleaned, split, and converted to msr and Chl units according to factory calibration.

Combine all data and produce meta table

  library(antics)

  # Load files that have been matched with CTD profiles to get depth
  knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "C:/Users/slcg/Dropbox/SOLSTICE/EK188")
  setwd("C:/Users/slcg/Dropbox/SOLSTICE/EK188")

  # load EcoTriplet data
  dat <- read.csv("EK188_EcoTriplet_all_casts.csv", header = T)

  # Get all file names
  file_list <- levels(as.factor(dat$Profile))
  
  # Remove empty file, and the too profiles that are too shallow (55 and 56)
  file_list <- file_list[!grepl("53|55|56",file_list)]
  
  # ignore unwanted profiles
  dat <- dat[!grepl("53|55|56", dat$Profile), ]

  # make empty data frame for meta data
  meta <- data.frame(Profile=character(),
                  Date=character(),
                  Time=character(),
                  Min_depth=numeric(), 
                  Max_depth=numeric(), 
                  Min_chl=numeric(), 
                  Max_chl=numeric(), 
                  stringsAsFactors=FALSE) 

  # loop through files
  for (i in 1:length(file_list)) {

    # load profile
    eco         <- dat[dat$Profile == file_list[i],]
    
    # if empty file, next
    if (nrow(eco)==0) {
      print(paste("File is empty. File:", file_list[i], sep=" "))
      next
    }

    # make meta 
    meta[i,"Profile"]   <- file_list[i]
    meta[i,"Date"]      <- as.character(eco$Date[1])
    meta[i,"Time"]      <- as.character(eco$Time[1])
    meta[i,"Min_depth"] <- min(eco$Depth)
    meta[i,"Max_depth"] <- max(eco$Depth)
    meta[i,"Min_chl"]   <- min(eco$Chl.ugL)
    meta[i,"Max_chl"]   <- max(eco$Chl.ugL)
  }

  # match with meta data
  meta$Nbr    <- as.numeric(as.character(stringr::str_extract(meta$Profile,"[0-9]{3}")))

  meta$CTD_ID <- ctd$ID[match(meta$Nbr, ctd$Nbr)]
  
  # delete missing row
  meta <- meta[!is.na(meta$Profile),]

Depth horizons

Filipa calculated depth horizons using a variety of metrics to determine surface and bottom mixed layer. After discussions with her, Margaux and Alex, we decided on the MLD1_n2, BLD01 and BLD02.

Column name Definition
CAST cast number
LAT cast latitude
LON cast longitude
dtime cast time In format yyyy-mmm-dd HH:MM:SS
max_ctd_pres maximum pressure recorded by the ctd cast
MLD125 MLD defined by 0.125 density difference from surface density reference
MLD_n2 max buoyancy frequency in the full cast
MLD1_n2 max buoyancy frequency between surface and a depth where the density is 0.8 kg m^-3 higher than the surface (just to cap it and not finding bottom layer)
QI125 Quality index for MLD 0.125 threshold (ideally want closer to 1 - anything below 0.5 is not defined, between 0.5 and 0.8 is defined with uncertainty, and over 0.8 is defined with certainty. The basis for this metric is an homogenous MLD, in this case I believe QIs are not super important because there are often 2-step MLs and the deeper one often matches the chlorophyll profile better. QIs are often higher in the MLD125 definition because it is capturing the active mixing layer.
QI_n2 Quality index for MLD defined by max(N^2) for the full cast
QI1_n2 Quality index for MLD defined by max(N^2)
MLD_CHL productive layer (= depth where we find 20% of the maximum chl in the profile - so always deeper than CHL max)
MLD_CHL_max depth of the chlorophyll maximum in the profile
CHL_max actual maximum chlorophyll concentration in the profile. Goes together with MLD_CHL_max
BLD01 depth of the bottom layer defined by the 0.01 threshold
BLD02 depth of the bottom layer defined by the 0.02 threshold
rmse_BLD01 root mean square error (where rmse_BLD=sqrt(nanmean(full water column sigma)-nanmean(sigma(BLD to the bottom)).^2)); for the BLD01 definition
rmse_BLD02 root mean square error (where rmse_BLD=sqrt(nanmean(full water column sigma)-nanmean(sigma(BLD to the bottom)).^2)); for the BLD02 definition
QI01_BLD quality index - applied the same definition as the MLD QI. These are generally very close to 1. Im using comparing to full water column sigma, instead of 1.5 MLD as previously defined by the paper
QI02_BLD same for BLD02 definition
bottom_ref_dens density used as reference density at the bottom; nanmedian(sigma) of the bottom 10m of the profile - used in BLD calculation
surf_ref_dens density used as reference density at the surface; nanmedian(sigma) of the bottom 8m of the profile - used in the MLD threshold calculations (I usually use a shallower depth, but we often dont have any data before 6-7m)
Delta sigma just difference of density between 2 depths
delta_sigma_surf_to_CHL_max surface to the depth of the chlorophyll maximum
delta_sigma_surf_to_MLD125 between surface and the MLD defined by the 0.125 threshold
delta_sigma_surf_to_40m delta sigma in the upper 40 m
delta_sigma_surf_to_MLD1_n2 this is MLD defined by max(N2) between the surface and a depth where density is 0.8 kg m-3 higher than the surface
delta_sigma_surf_to_MLD_n2 this MLD is defined by max(N^2) in the whole profile
delta_sigma_BLD01_minus_5m simple difference in sigma between the bottom layer depth (0.01 definition) and 5 m above that depth
max_n2_at_MLD_n2 max of N^2 at the depth of MLD defined by max(N^2)
max_n2_at_MLD1_n2 max of N^2 at the depth of MLD defined by max(N^2) between surface and the depth where density is 0.8 kg m-3 higher than the surface

Backscatter spike analysis

The sensor signal is partitioned into three components:

F = l + s + r +

where the full signal (F) is a composed of large (l), small (s), a blank value (r) and noise ().

The blank value was calculated from deep profiles recorded during COMICS2, and they have been subtracted during the conversion (EcoPuck_processing_2). Hence:

r = 0

The noise was calculated as the standard deviation of the blank value (EcoPuck_processing_2) (see Table).

_ ECO Chlorophyll Fluorometer Scattering meter at 700 nm Scattering meter at 532 nm
Scale Factor - factory (SFf) 0.0305 ug/L/count 3.004E-06 (m-1sr-1)/counts 6.974E-06 (m-1sr-1)/counts
Scale Factor - measured (SFm) 0.0626 ug/L/count N/A N/A
Dark Counts (deep casts) 47 5 counts 62 6 counts 27 5 counts
Uncertainty 0.313 ug/L 1.8024e-05 m-1sr-1 3.487e-05 m-1sr-1

Small particles are here associated as the baseline signal and are calculated using a running minimum. Baseline signal is calculated according to Briggs in a two 2-step process:

  1. Running minimum 11-point (high frequency data hence higher running mean value)
  2. Running maximum 11-point

This process assumes that there are frequent periods when no large particles are present. This assumption does not work for our cruise, so I therefore only use the running minimum (Step 1).

A considerable number of data points was <0 for all frequencies. Such values are to be expected if we are sampling an environment where particle concentrations are very low (not detectable). I set all negative values for small particles as 0. As I am ignoring negative noise values but not positive noise, I effectively biase my data positively (by +).

(F < 0) = F - == 0

s + = rmin(F){i-5:i+5} +

Residual spikes (large particles) are then calculated by removing the baseline signal. Note. I am here subtracting the positive biase introduced in the previous step (+).

l = F - (s + )

Note, the unit of backscatter is:

m-1: per meter sr-1: per steradian

  # remove negative values
  dat$B532.msr0 <- dat$B532.msr; dat$B532.msr0[dat$B532.msr < 0] <- 0
  dat$B700.msr0 <- dat$B700.msr; dat$B700.msr0[dat$B700.msr < 0] <- 0
  dat$Chl.ugL0  <- dat$Chl.ugL;  dat$Chl.ugL0 [dat$Chl.ugL  < 0] <- 0

  # percentage below 0
  table(dat$B532.msr < 0) / nrow(dat)

## 0.7642516 0.2357484
  table(dat$B700.msr < 0) / nrow(dat)

## 0.96131968 0.03868032
  table(dat$Chl.ugL  < 0) / nrow(dat)

The data looks good for B700 and Chl: The positive biase introduced by setting negative values to 0 is well below the SD. For B532, the biase is higher, suggesting that we removed more than what is expected from the SD.

  # loop through files
  for (i in unique(dat$Profile)) {

    # Extract individual profiles
    eco <- dat[dat$Profile==i,]
    
    # 1. Running minimum 11-point (high frequency data hence higher running mean value)
    eco$B532_rmin <- running_min(eco$B532.msr0)
    eco$B700_rmin <- running_min(eco$B700.msr0) 
    eco$Chl_rmin  <- running_min(eco$Chl.ugL0) 

    # Calculate spikes by removing baseline signal
    eco$B532_Spike <- eco$B532.msr0-eco$B532_rmin
    eco$B700_Spike <- eco$B700.msr0-eco$B700_rmin
    eco$Chl_Spike  <- eco$Chl.ugL0-eco$Chl_rmin

    # Add values to main df
    dat$B532_Basel[dat$Profile==i] <- eco$B532_rmin
    dat$B700_Basel[dat$Profile==i] <- eco$B700_rmin
    dat$Chl_Basel[dat$Profile==i]  <- eco$Chl_rmin

    dat$B532_Spike[dat$Profile==i] <- eco$B532_Spike
    dat$B700_Spike[dat$Profile==i] <- eco$B700_Spike
    dat$Chl_Spike[dat$Profile==i]  <- eco$Chl_Spike
  }

I separated background noise from spikes. I hence split 1 observation into 2 parts.

I here check the histogrammes to see how this affected the distributions.

  prob <- function(x, breaks=breaks, ...) {
    h <- hist(x, breaks=breaks, plot=FALSE)
    h$counts <- h$counts/sum(h$counts)
    plot(h, ...)
  }

  sub <- eco[eco$B700.msr0 <= quantile(eco$B700.msr,0.95),]

  par(mfrow=c(2,2))
  breaks <- seq(min(sub$B700.msr0), max(sub$B700.msr), length.out=20)
  prob(sub$B700.msr0 , breaks=breaks, ylim=c(0,0.6), main="raw data (>0)")
  prob(sub$B700_Basel, breaks=breaks, ylim=c(0,0.6), main="baseline")
  prob(sub$B700_Spike, breaks=breaks, ylim=c(0,0.6), main="spikes")
  prob(c(sub$B700_Basel, sub$B700_Spike), breaks=breaks, ylim=c(0,0.5), main="baseline + spikes")

  par(mfrow=c(3,2))
  hist(dat$B700_Basel, main="Baseline (700 nm)", breaks=100)
  hist(dat$B700_Spike, main="Spikes (700 nm)", breaks=100)

  hist(log(dat$B700_Basel), main="log Baseline (700 nm)", breaks=100)
  hist(log(dat$B700_Spike), main="log Spikes (700 nm)", breaks=100)

  hist(sqrt(dat$B700_Basel), main="sqrt Baseline (700 nm)", breaks=100)
  hist(sqrt(dat$B700_Spike), main="sqrt Spikes (700 nm)", breaks=100)

Ok, looking at the histogramme, I have to useful populations! Winning! Note that the log-transformation deletes all zero observations, so the sqrt() transformed data is a better representation of the true distribution. The log() distribution shows that, when observed, spike height is normally distributed.

Depth bins

For spike analysis, the depth needs to be binned. I here decided on 2-m bins. Each bin starts at the nominal depth and extends for a further 2 m. For example, bin 4 ranges from 4 - 6 m depth.

  bin_size      <- 2
  z_bin         <- function(x) {floor(x/bin_size)*bin_size}
  dat$Depth_bin <- z_bin(dat$Depth)

From the plots it becomes very clear that more spikes are recorded when lingering at a depth, such as near 2 m during the downcast, and during bottle firing on the upcast.

Profiling speed affects spike height.

Nathan also explained that the descend/ascend speed affects spike height. The approximate bbp sample volume is just under 1 ml. This means that a particle path through the sample volume is on the order of 1 cm or less. So when profiling at 1m/s, each particle spends <0.01 s in the sample volume. At highest resolution, each bbp (or chl) measurement reported represents an average over ~ 1/16 s. This means that a spike-causing particle will only be in the sample volume for <1/6 of the sample integration time at that speed. So a single spike measurement will be an average of samples with and without the particle, meaning that the height of the spike will be 1/6 as high when the bbp sensor is moving at 1 m/s as it would be when it is still. This means that the threshold between spike and non-spike can potentially change with platform speed. This may contribute to differences you see when waiting for bottles on the upcast. This also means that the downcast (if profiling speed is consistent) is probably best for your cluster analysis.

I will check profiling speed here. I noticed that readings always come in sets of 8. So I need to set the cummulative interval to >8.

  dat$Datetime      <- strptime(paste(dat$Date, dat$Time, sep=" "), format="%m/%d/%y %H:%M:%S", tz="GMT")

  running_sum <- function(arr, n=11){
    res = arr
    for (i in n:length(arr)) {
      res[i] = sum(arr[(i-n):i])
    }
    res
  }

I found the following criteria seem to work reasonably well. I calcualte speed over 24 readings, which is typically 2 seconds (16 readings). Only values that were between 0.2 - 1.0 m/s were used. This means that the maximum difference in spike height due to differences in speed is a factor of 5. Still high, but only 53% of the data meet these criteria.

I will also exclude shallow samples: The spikes near the surface are likely to include bubbles. On the downcast, this includes bubbles from the sensor entering the water. On the upcast this includes natural bubbles from waves and also perhaps from the ship. So I guess I would advise not to include the top 2-5 m.

I here opted for 4 m because of the bin-sizes (i.e.bin 4 extends from 4-6 m.)

Some depth bins have not values (e.g.removed during quality control, e.g.because of wrong sampling speed). I will interpolate these bins using quasi-linear regressions.

  bb_int <- bb

  df      <- bb_int[0,]
  counter <- 1
  
  # ---- Interpolate ----
  # Interpolate missing depth bins
  for (i in bb_int$Order){
    x <- bb_int[bb_int$Order %in% i ,]
    
    # find max depth
    z_max <- max(bb_int[bb_int$Order %in% i ,]$Depth)

    # define bins that should be there
    SEQ <- seq(4, z_max, by=2)

    # find missing bins
    missing <- SEQ[(SEQ %in% bb_int[bb_int$Order %in% i ,]$Depth)==FALSE]
    there   <- SEQ[(SEQ %in% bb_int[bb_int$Order %in% i ,]$Depth)==TRUE]

    # make new row
    for (k in missing){

      shallow <- max(there[there<k])
      deep    <- min(there[there>k])

      # if no data to interpolate, next
      if (any(is.infinite(shallow), is.infinite(deep))) next

      # find row number of bin above
      ROW     <- which(bb_int$Order %in% i & bb_int$Depth %in% shallow)
      
      # make new row by copying the bin above
      new_row <- bb_int[ROW,]
      rownames(new_row) <- paste("int", counter, sep="")

      # replace depth
      new_row$Depth <- k

      # interpolate values
      new_row[,c("B532_B", "B532_S", "B700_B", "B700_S", "Chl_B", "Chl_S")] <- 
        colMeans(bb_int[bb_int$Order %in% i & bb_int$Depth %in% c(shallow, deep),
                 c("B532_B", "B532_S", "B700_B", "B700_S", "Chl_B", "Chl_S")])

      # add to df
      bb_int <- rbind(bb_int, new_row)

      # increase counter
      counter <- counter + 1
    }
  }

  # Make negative depth for plotting
  bb_int$Depth_neg <- bb_int$Depth * -1

Backscatter ratios

The two backscatter frequencies are strongly correlated, which opens the questions whether the distinction between the two frequencies is useful. To explore this, I here calculate the ratio between the baselines of green (532 nm) and red (700 nm) particles. Areas in the plot that has a blue -ish colour indicate a higher proportion of bp532, red -ish colours indicate more bp700. The plot clearly shows that the ratio between the two particle populations varies considerably, with bp532 increasing in proportion near the benthos and in regions with high fluorescence.
